# IPv4 Addressing

## Overview

IPv4 (Internet Protocol Version 4) is the most widely used protocol for identifying devices on a network.

An IPv4 address consists of **32 bits** divided into **4 octets**.

Example:

192.168.1.10

Each octet ranges from **0 to 255**.

---

## Structure

Example Address

192.168.1.10

| Octet | Value |
|-------|-------|
| 1 | 192 |
| 2 | 168 |
| 3 | 1 |
| 4 | 10 |

---

## Public vs Private IP Addresses

### Private Address Ranges

| Range | CIDR |
|--------|------|
| 10.0.0.0 - 10.255.255.255 | /8 |
| 172.16.0.0 - 172.31.255.255 | /12 |
| 192.168.0.0 - 192.168.255.255 | /16 |

Private addresses are used inside organizations and homes.

Public IP addresses are assigned by Internet Service Providers (ISPs).

---

## IPv4 Classes

| Class | Range | Default Mask |
|--------|--------|--------------|
| A | 1–126 | 255.0.0.0 |
| B | 128–191 | 255.255.0.0 |
| C | 192–223 | 255.255.255.0 |
| D | 224–239 | Multicast |
| E | 240–255 | Experimental |

